{{also|DOG|d√∂g}} ==English==
{{slim-wikipedia}} [[Image:YellowLabradorLooking.jpg|thumb|A dog (a [[Labrador retriever]])]]
===Alternative forms=== * [[darg]], [[dawg]] {{qualifier|dialectal}}; [[doggie]], [[doggy]] {{qualifier|childish}}
===Pronunciation=== * {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/d…í…°/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/dQg/}} * {{a|US}} {{IPA|/d…î…°/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/dOg/}} * {{a|US|Canada|cot-caught}} {{IPA|/d…ë…°/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/dAg/}} * {{audio|en-us-dog.ogg|Audio (US)}} * {{audio|En-uk-a dog.ogg|Audio (UK)}} * {{rhymes|…í…°}}
===Etymology=== From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|dogge|lang=enm|sc=Latn}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|docga|lang=ang||hound, powerful breed of dog|sc=Latinx}}, a pet-form diminutive of {{etyl|ang|-}} {{recons|docce|docce|lang=ang|muscle}} (found in compound {{term|fingerdocce||lang=ang|finger-muscle|sc=Latinx}} with suffix {{term|-ga|-ga|lang=ang|sc=Latinx}} (compare {{term|frocga||lang=ang|frog|sc=Latinx}}, {{term|picga||lang=ang|pig|sc=Latinx}}). The true origin is unknown, but one possibility is from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|dukk≈çn||power, strength, muscle|lang=gem-pro}}, though this may just be confusion with [[dock]]. In the 16th century, it superseded {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|hund|lang=ang|sc=Latinx}} and was adopted by many continental European languages.<ref>{{R:Online Etymology Dictionary|dog}}</ref>
===Noun=== {{en-noun}}
# A mammal, ''[[Canis lupus familiaris]]'', of the genus ''[[Canis]]'' that has been [[domesticated]] for thousands of years, of highly variable appearance due to human breeding. #: ''The '''dog''' barked all night long.'' # A male dog, [[wolf]] or [[fox]], as opposed to a [[bitch]] (a female dog, wolf or fox). # {{derogatory}} A dull, unattractive [[girl]] or [[woman]]. #: ''She‚Äôs a real '''dog'''.'' # {{slang}} A [[man]]. #: ''You lucky '''dog'''!'' # {{slang|derogatory}} A [[coward]] #: ''Come back and fight, you '''dogs'''!'' # {{derogatory}} Someone who is morally reprehensible. #: ''You dirty '''dog'''.'' #* '''1599''' ‚Äî Robert Greene, ''Alphonsus, King of Aragon'' (1599). Act 3. #*: Blasphemous '''dog''', I wonder that the earth #*: Doth cease from renting vnderneath thy feete, #*: To swallow vp those cankred corpes of thine. # Any of various mechanical devices for holding, gripping, or fastening something, particularly with a tooth-like projection. # {{rfc-def}} A [[click]] or [[pallet]] adapted to engage the teeth of a ratchet-wheel, to restrain the back action; a click or pawl. (See also: [[ratchet]], [[windlass]]) # A metal support for [[log]]s in a fireplace. #: ''The '''dogs''' were too hot to touch.'' #* '''1902''', [[w:Arthur Conan Doyle|Arthur Conan Doyle]], ''[[s:The Hound of the Baskervilles|The Hound of the Baskervilles]]'' #*: In the great old-fashioned fireplace behind the high iron '''dogs''' a log-fire crackled and snapped. # A [[hot dog]]. # {{poker|_|slang}} [[underdog|Underdog]] # {{slang|almost always|_|in the plural}} [[foot|feet]]. #: "My '''dogs''' are barking!" meaning "My feet hurt!"
